{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2f50df7b-8e1f-4695-a22d-09e021e7a482","content":"You're on **MSTest 3.8.2 / .NET 9**, so you have access to the modern patterns.\n\n**Recommended approach:**\n\n- **Constructor** — for synchronous setup and `TestContext` injection\n- **`[TestInitialize]` async method** — for async setup (runs before each test)\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests\n{\n    private readonly TestContext _testContext;\n    private MyService _service;\n\n    // Sync init + TestContext injection via constructor\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        _testContext = testContext;\n        _service = new MyService();\n    }\n\n    // Async init (runs before each test)\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public async Task SetupAsync()\n    {\n        await _service.ConnectAsync();\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public async Task MyTest()\n    {\n        _testContext.WriteLine(\"Running test...\");\n        // ...\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points for MSTest 3.x:**\n- **Constructor injection** of `TestContext` is the modern way (no need for the legacy `public TestContext TestContext { get; set; }` property).\n- `[TestInitialize]` supports `async Task` return types.\n- Put synchronous setup in the constructor, async setup in `[TestInitialize]`.\n- For class-level async setup, use `[ClassInitialize]` (static, also supports async).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8ec51521-4215-46e5-9229-9db33c67580a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"They're using MSTest 3.8.2 on .NET 9.0. In MSTest v3, the recommended modern approach is:\n\n1. **TestContext injection**: Use a constructor parameter or the `public TestContext TestContext { get; set; }` property. In MSTest 3.x, constructor injection is supported.\n\n2. **Synchronous initialization**: Use `[TestInitialize]` method or constructor.\n\n3. **Asynchronous initialization**: Use `[TestInitialize]` with an async method (supported in MSTest v3).\n\nActually, let me be more precise about MSTest 3.x features:\n\n\n- `[TestInitialize]` can be async (return `Task`).\n- `TestContext` can be injected via constructor in MSTest 3.x.\n- You can also use `[ClassInitialize]` for class-level init.\n\nThe modern MSTest v3 approach combines constructor injection for `TestContext` with either synchronous or asynchronous `[TestInitialize]` methods—you can even use both together if needed. Let me put together a clear recommendation.","outputTokens":633,"requestId":"7686:18DC0C:B99AB7:D7D805:69F2B094"},"id":"9054a0c3-6ac1-4e6c-afef-aaecd6f6da7a","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:30:09.465Z","parentId":"30ae55c8-b1a8-49fd-9af3-cbb62911ace4"}
